Excellent and really easy. I don't have a spaetzle maker, so I just pushed the batter through the holes of a colander. I used the spaetzle in place of noodles in my favorite baked mac'n'cheese recipe. Delicious!

Rating: 2
This is pretty good, coming from Germany I'm pretty familiar with spaetzle. Personally I prefer making spaetzle and mixing it with a simple cheese sauce and extra cubed cheese, place it all in a casserole. Brown a sliced onion in butter (until really dark) and place on top of the casserole. Heat through in a 350 oven for 20-30 minutes. It's a classic south German (Swabian) dish, sort of like macaroni & cheese. Another version is to do the same as I just said, but stir in a can of tomatoes - chopped. Simple and good - real home German cooking. To the last reviewer - you can get a spaetzle maker at any cookware store for about $15.

